      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Land Tax Clearance Certificates and Adjustments When Selling in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Land tax can create settlement complications that sellers do not anticipate. Here is what you need to know about clearance certificates, adjustments, and how Queensland's system works.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Land tax is one of those costs that many property owners either forget about or have never needed to think about, because their primary residence is exempt. When you move to sell an investment property, vacant land, or a property held in a company or trust, land tax becomes relevant again, and it can affect settlement in ways that catch sellers unprepared. The clearance certificate process exists to give both parties a clear picture of any liabilities before the transaction completes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a land tax clearance certificate is</h2>
      <p>A land tax clearance certificate is a formal document issued by the Queensland Revenue Office (QRO) that states the land tax status of a property as at a specific date. It confirms whether any land tax is outstanding, whether the property is subject to a land tax liability, and whether any charges have been registered against the title.</p>

      <p>At settlement, your solicitor or conveyancer will typically request a clearance certificate as part of standard conveyancing procedure. The buyer's solicitor needs confirmation that no land tax liability is attached to the property that would pass to the new owner at settlement. Without that clearance, settlement can be delayed while the liability is investigated or resolved.</p>

      <p>For residential properties used as the owner's principal place of residence, Queensland land tax does not generally apply, and a clearance certificate may not be required. For investment properties, vacant land, and properties owned through companies, trusts, or self-managed super funds, land tax is likely to be applicable and the clearance certificate process is part of standard settlement procedure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How land tax is assessed in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Queensland land tax is calculated based on the unimproved value of land you own as at 30 June each year, excluding your principal place of residence. If the total taxable value of your land holdings exceeds the threshold (which changes over time), you are liable for land tax on the amount above the threshold.</p>

      <p>The Queensland Revenue Office issues land tax assessments each year, usually in the period from September to March for the prior 30 June valuation date. Land tax is assessed on a yearly basis, not on a per-property basis, which means your liability for a single investment property depends on the total value of all your taxable land holdings across Queensland. If you own multiple investment properties, they are all counted together when assessing your threshold position.</p>

      <p>This structure creates a potential complication for sellers. The land tax assessment you receive relates to your entire portfolio position as at 30 June. If you sell a property partway through the year, the settlement adjustment accounts for the portion of the year during which you owned the property, but the underlying assessment is still calculated on your full portfolio position as at the previous June. Your solicitor should be across this when calculating the settlement adjustment figures.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How land tax is adjusted at settlement</h2>
      <p>Land tax is adjusted at settlement on a daily pro-rata basis within the financial year. The seller is responsible for the land tax attributable to the period from 1 July through to and including the settlement date. The buyer is responsible for the period from the day after settlement through to 30 June.</p>

      <p>If the land tax for the full year has already been paid, the seller may be entitled to a credit for the portion that relates to the period after settlement. If land tax has not yet been paid for the year and an assessment is outstanding, the settlement statement will include an amount held in trust or credited to the buyer to cover their proportionate share.</p>

      <p>This adjustment is handled by the solicitors and reflected in the settlement statement. It is not usually something the seller needs to manage directly, provided the solicitor has been given accurate information about the property's land tax status and any outstanding assessments.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if land tax arrears exist</h2>
      <p>If land tax has not been paid and arrears have accumulated, the QRO can register a charge against the property's title. This charge attaches to the land rather than to the individual owner, which means a buyer purchasing a property with an unresolved land tax charge on title would inherit the liability. This is exactly the risk the clearance certificate process is designed to prevent.</p>

      <p>If your solicitor identifies a registered land tax charge during title searches, the standard approach is to resolve it before settlement. This typically involves the seller paying the outstanding amount, or making arrangements for it to be paid from sale proceeds at settlement, and obtaining confirmation from the QRO that the charge has been discharged before the title transfers.</p>

      <p>Arrears situations can arise for a range of reasons: assessments sent to an old address, changes in portfolio structure that triggered liability without the owner realising, or properties that were believed to be exempt but were not. If you have not been actively tracking your land tax position across your property portfolio, it is worth having your solicitor check the title position as early in the sale process as possible.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The QRO clearance request process and timeline</h2>
      <p>The Queensland Revenue Office processes land tax clearance requests submitted by solicitors through the QRO's online system. The processing time can vary depending on the complexity of the property's history and the current workload of the QRO, but solicitors generally recommend allowing at least two weeks before the settlement date for the clearance to be obtained and any issues to be resolved.</p>

      <p>For properties with uncomplicated land tax histories, clearances are often processed more quickly. For properties with complex ownership structures, multiple title parcels, or any outstanding liabilities, more time should be allowed. If your settlement date is firm and relatively close, tell your solicitor early so they can prioritise the clearance request.</p>

      <p>If issues arise during the QRO process, it is not necessarily a reason to panic, but it is a reason to act quickly. Delays in resolving land tax issues are one of the more common causes of settlement adjournments, and adjournments have their own costs and risks, including the possibility that the buyer's finance expires or that settlement falls over entirely.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common land tax surprises and how to avoid them</h2>
      <p>The most common surprise is finding an assessment for a year where the seller believed the property was exempt. Principal place of residence exemptions require the property to have been genuinely used as the owner's home for the relevant period. If you rented the property out for part of a year, moved out before 30 June, or moved in after 30 June, the exemption may not have applied for that year. Some sellers only discover this when the clearance search reveals a historical assessment.</p>

      <p>A second common issue involves properties held in trusts or companies. The land tax rules for non-individual owners differ from those for individuals, and the thresholds and surcharges that apply can be significantly higher. Sellers who hold investment properties through structures should check the land tax history of those properties well before listing.</p>

      <p>A third issue arises when properties are held by multiple owners. Each owner's share of the property is added to their individual total land holdings for threshold purposes. Owners who are already at or near the threshold from other holdings may find that adding a jointly owned property creates a liability they had not expected.</p>

      <p>None of these issues is insurmountable, but they are much easier to address before you have a buyer under contract and a settlement date locked in. If you are selling an investment property in Queensland, instruct your solicitor to check the land tax position as soon as you decide to sell, rather than waiting until contracts are exchanged.</p>

